:ITN068 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN068" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Increased risk of kidney damage (AKI), elevated creatinine" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Possible additive nephrotoxicity when given concurrently" ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Monitor renal function (BUN, creatinine), ensure hydration, adjust dose if needed" ;
    :hasReference :R032 ;
    :interactsWith :S038 .

:ITN069 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN069" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Increased risk of bleeding, elevated INR" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Cefuroxime may enhance anticoagulant effect" ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Monitor INR closely, adjust anticoagulant dose as needed" ;
    :hasReference :R032 ;
    :interactsWith :S039 .

:ITN070 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN070" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Reduced clearance by inhibiting renal tubular secretion" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Penicillins may decrease renal clearance" ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Carefully monitor patients receiving both concomitantly" ;
    :hasReference :R017 ;
    :interactsWith :S044 .

:ITN071 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN071" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Slows renal secretion, producing higher and prolonged serum levels" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Administered shortly before or with amoxicillin" ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Management should be overseen by a physician" ;
    :hasReference :R017 ;
    :interactsWith :S045 .

:ITN072 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN072" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Increases the incidence and possibility of skin rashes" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Concurrent administration" ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Monitor for skin reactions during treatment" ;
    :hasReference :R017 ;
    :interactsWith :S046 .

:ITN073 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN073" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "May cause breakthrough bleeding and reduce birth control effectiveness" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Concomitant use with penicillins" ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Consider additional contraceptive measures" ;
    :hasReference :R017 ;
    :interactsWith :S047 .

:ITN074 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN074" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Has no significant influence on amoxicillin absorption" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Ingestion alongside the medication" ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "May be taken with meals to reduce Gastrointestinal discomfort and improve absorption" ;
    :hasReference :R017 ;
    :interactsWith :S048 .

:ITN075 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN075" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Inhibits renal tubular secretion, increasing drug levels" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Concurrent use with aminopenicillins" ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Carefully monitor clinical status during co-administration" ;
    :hasReference :R017 ;
    :interactsWith :S049 .

:ITN076 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN076" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Produces higher and prolonged serum concentrations" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Taken simultaneously or shortly before" ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Physician supervision recommended" ;
    :hasReference :R017 ;
    :interactsWith :S050 .

:ITN077 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN077" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Increases incidence of skin rashes, especially in hyperuricemic patients" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Concurrent administration" ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Monitor for allergic manifestations" ;
    :hasReference :R017 ;
    :interactsWith :S051 .

:ITN078 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN078" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Reduces effectiveness and may cause breakthrough bleeding" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Concomitant use" ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Patient should be informed of reduced efficacy" ;
    :hasReference :R017 ;
    :interactsWith :S052 .

:ITN079 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN079" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Absorption is 90% and is not significantly affected by food" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Taking medication during meals" ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "May be taken with meals for better absorption and less Gastrointestinal discomfort" ;
    :hasReference :R017 ;
    :interactsWith :S053 .

:ITN080 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN080" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Pancytopenia, marrow suppression, increased toxicity" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Sulfonamides such as sulfamethoxazole may displace methotrexate from protein binding sites and can compete with the renal transport of methotrexate, thereby increasing free methotrexate levels. Cases of pancytopenia have been reported in patients taking the combination of sulfamethoxazole/trimethoprim and methotrexate." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Avoid combination. Monitor for increased free methotrexate and marrow suppression." ;
    :hasReference :R035 ;
    :interactsWith :S054 .

:ITN081 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN081" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Reduced antibacterial effectiveness of TMP‑SMX" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Para-aminobenzoic acid (PABA) or its derivatives may antagonise the antibacterial effects of sulfamethoxazole." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Avoid PABA supplements. They may reduce TMP‑SMX efficacy." ;
    :hasReference :R035 ;
    :interactsWith :S055 .

:ITN082 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN082" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Prolonged PT/INR, increased bleeding risk" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Anticoagulant activity may be increased by concurrent treatment with sulfamethoxazole/trimethoprim. It has been reported that sulfamethoxazole/trimethoprim may prolong the prothrombin time in patients who are receiving the anticoagulant warfarin (a CYP2C9 substrate). This interaction should be kept in mind when sulfamethoxazole/trimethoprim is given to patients already on anticoagulant therapy, and the coagulation time should be reassessed." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Monitor INR/PT. Adjust dose to avoid over-anticoagulation." ;
    :hasReference :R035 ;
    :interactsWith :S056 .

:ITN083 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN083" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Phenytoin toxicity. Nystagmus, ataxia, confusion" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Increased effects and side effects of phenytoin (folate deficiencies) could occur when sulfamethoxazole/trimethoprim is given concurrently. Sulfamethoxazole/trimethoprim may inhibit the hepatic metabolism of phenytoin (a CYP2C9 substrate). Oral sulfamethoxazole/trimethoprim, given at a common clinical dosage, increased the phenytoin half-life by 39% and decreased the phenytoin metabolic clearance rate by 27%. When administering these drugs concurrently, one should be alert for possible excessive phenytoin effect." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Monitor levels and for toxicity. Adjust dose as needed." ;
    :hasReference :R035 ;
    :interactsWith :S057 .

:ITN084 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN084" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Hypoglycemia" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Concomitant use may result in potentiation of hypoglycaemia in occasional patients." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Monitor blood glucose for potentiated hypoglycemia." ;
    :hasReference :R035 ;
    :interactsWith :S058 .

:ITN085 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN085" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Thrombocytopenia, purpura" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "An increased incidence of thrombocytopenia is reported when this combination is used in the elderly." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Monitor for thrombocytopenia. Avoid if high risk." ;
    :hasReference :R035 ;
    :interactsWith :S059 .

:ITN086 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN086" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Reversible nephrotoxicity" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription """Deterioration in renal function in patients with renal transplants. There have been reports of marked but reversible nephrotoxicity with co-\r
administration of sulfamethoxazole/trimethoprim and ciclosporin in renal transplant recipients.""" ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Avoid combination if possible. Monitor renal function." ;
    :hasReference :R035 ;
    :interactsWith :S060 .

:ITN087 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN087" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Megaloblastic anemia" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Occasional reports suggest that patients receiving pyrimethamine as malarial prophylaxis at doses in excess of 25 mg weekly may develop megaloblastic anaemia should sulfamethoxazole/trimethoprim be prescribed concurrently." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Avoid combination. Monitor CBC for anemia." ;
    :hasReference :R035 ;
    :interactsWith :S061 .

:ITN088 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN088" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Digoxin toxicity which includes nausea, arrhythmias" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Concomitant use of trimethoprim with digoxin has been shown to increase plasma digoxin levels in a proportion of elderly patients. Serum digoxin levels should be monitored." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Monitor serum digoxin. Adjust dose to avoid toxicity." ;
    :hasReference :R035 ;
    :interactsWith :S062 .

:ITN089 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN089" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Hyperkalemia" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Due to the potassium sparing effects of sulfamethoxazole/trimethoprim, caution should be used when other agents that increase serum potassium, such as angiotensin converting enzyme inhibitors, angiotensin receptor blockers, potassium sparing diuretics and prednisolone, are co-administered. In the literature, two cases of hyperkalaemia in elderly patients have been reported after concomitant intake of sulfamethoxazole/trimethoprim and an angiotensin converting enzyme inhibitor." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Monitor serum potassium. Avoid in high-risk patients." ;
    :hasReference :R035 ;
    :interactsWith :S063 .

:ITN090 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN090" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Decreased TCA efficacy" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "The efficacy of tricyclic antidepressants can decrease when co-administered with sulfamethoxazole/trimethoprim." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Monitor therapeutic response. Adjust TCA dose if efficacy decreases." ;
    :hasReference :R035 ;
    :interactsWith :S064 .

:ITN091 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN091" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Increased TMP-SMX blood levels, risk of adverse effects" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "May occur in patients who are also receiving urinary acidifiers, oral anticoagulants, phenylbutazone, oxyphenbutazone and indomethacin." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Avoid combination. Monitor for toxicity." ;
    :hasReference :R035 ;
    :interactsWith :S065 .

:ITN092 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN092" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Increased drug levels or potentiation, hypoglycemia, toxicity" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Trimethoprim is an inhibitor of CYP2C8 as well as an OCT2 transporter. Sulfamethoxazole is an inhibitor of CYP2C9. Caution is recommended when DBL Sulfamethoxazole 400 mg and Trimethoprim 80 mg is co-administered with drugs that are substrates of CYP2C8 and 2C9 or OCT2. Sulfamethoxazole/trimethoprim potentiates the effect of oral hypoglycaemics that are metabolised by CYP2C8 (e.g. pioglitazone, repaglinide, and rosiglitazone) or CYP2C9 (e.g. glipizide and glyburide) or eliminated renally via OCT2 (e.g. metformin). Additional monitoring of blood glucose may be warranted." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Monitor for altered effects. Adjust therapy based on response." ;
    :hasReference :R035 ;
    :interactsWith :S066 .

:ITN093 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN093" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Elevated dofetilide levels is linear with QT prolongation, torsade de pointes, serious ventricular arrhythmias" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Concurrent administration is contraindicated. Elevated plasma concentrations of dofetilide have been reported following concurrent administration of trimethoprim and dofetilide. Increased plasma concentrations of dofetilide may cause serious ventricular arrhythmias associated with QT interval prolongation, including torsade de pointes." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Contraindicated with TMP‑SMX. Avoid co-administration" ;
    :hasReference :R035 ;
    :interactsWith :S067 .

:ITN094 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN094" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Increased plasma levels, risk of toxicity" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "When trimethoprim is administered simultaneously with drugs that form cations at physiological pH, and are also partly excreted by active renal secretion (e.g. procainamide, amantadine), there is the possibility of competitive inhibition of this process which may lead to an increase in plasma concentration of one or both of the drugs." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Monitor drug levels. Watch for increased plasma concentrations." ;
    :hasReference :R035 ;
    :interactsWith :S068 .

:ITN095 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN095" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Increased incidence of skin rashes, especially in hyperuricemic patients." ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Concurrent use with amoxicillin." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Inform your doctor if you are taking allopurinol" ;
    :hasReference :R016 ;
