:ITN246 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN246" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Higher levels of nitrofurantoin in the body can increase the risk of side effects such as nausea, liver problems, nerve issues, and general toxicity." ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "This drug reduces the kidney's ability to remove nitrofurantoin from the body, which can make the antibiotic stay longer in the bloodstream." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Avoid taking probenecid and nitrofurantoin together. If combination is necessary, monitor closely for side effects and adjust dosage under medical supervision." ;
    :hasReference :R158 ;
    :interactsWith :S165 .

:ITN247 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN247" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Reduced absorption can make the antibiotic less effective at treating urinary tract infections, potentially allowing the bacteria to persist or worsen." ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Antacids that contain magnesium can bind with nitrofurantoin in the stomach or intestines and reduce how much of the drugs is absorbed into the blood." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Do not take nitrofurantoin at the same time as magnesium-containing antacids. Take the antibiotic at least 2 hours before or after antacids to ensure proper absorption." ;
    :hasReference :R157 ;
    :interactsWith :S166 .

:ITN248 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN248" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Reduced antibacterial effectiveness can lead to slower infections recovery, persistent infection, or increased risk of bacterial resistance." ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "When taken together, fluoroquinolone antibiotics may have an antagonistic effect on nitrofurantoin, meaning the two drugs can interfere with each other's ability to kill bacteria." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Avoid combining nitrofurantoin with fluoroquinolone antibiotics unless directed by a doctor. If both are needed, careful monitoring and alternative dosing strategies may be required." ;
    :hasReference :R159 ;
    :interactsWith :S167 .

:ITN249 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN249" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Because less Macrobid reaches your bloodstream and urine, the infection may not get treated properly. You may have ongoing symptoms of urinary tract infection like pain, burning, or frequent urination." ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Antacids that contain magnesium trisilicate can stick to Macrobid in your stomach and gut, which lowers the amount of the antibiotic that your body can absorb. This makes Macrobid less able to fight the bacteria causing your infection." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Avoid taking these antacids while on Macrobid. If you must take an antacid, separate the doses by at least 2-3 hours. Always tell your doctor or pharmacist about any antacids you are using." ;
    :hasReference :R161 ;
    :interactsWith :S168 .

:ITN250 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN250" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Higher blood levels can increase your risk of side effects like nausea, headache, or nerve problems. Lower urine levels may make Macrobid less effective, leading to persistent urinary infections." ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Drugs like probenecid or sulfinpyrazone (used for gout) can block the way your kidneys remove Macrobid from your blood. This can cause higher levels of the drug in your body but lower levels in your urine where it is needed to fight bacteria." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Your doctor may monitor your blood and urine closely if you take these drugs with Macrobid. They may adjust your dose or suggest using a different medication combination to avoid problems." ;
    :hasReference :R161 ;
    :interactsWith :S169 .

:ITN252 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN252" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Higher blood levels may increase risk of side effects such as nausea, dizziness, or neuropathy, while lower drug concentration in urine can reduce effectiveness against urinary infections." ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Probenecid, a uricosuric drug, can reduce kidney excretion of Furadantin, increasing drug levels in the blood." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Monitor for side effects. Your doctor may adjust doses of Furadantin or the uricosuric drug. Report any persistent urinary symptoms." ;
    :hasReference :R163 ;
    :interactsWith :S171 .

:ITN253 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN253" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Blood levels of Furadantin may rise, increasing side effect risks, while effectiveness in treating urinary tract infections may decrease." ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Sulfinpyrazone, another uricosuric agent, can similarly interfere with kidney excretion of Furadantin." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Monitor for side effects and infection signs. Your doctor may need to adjust treatment. Avoid combining without supervision." ;
    :hasReference :R163 ;
    :interactsWith :S172 .

:ITN254 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN254" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "This may reduce the effectiveness of Furadantin in treating urinary infections, though exact clinical impact is uncertain." ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Propantheline, an anticholinergic drug, can alter kidney excretion of Furadantin, slightly changing how much antibiotic reaches the urine." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Your doctor may monitor infection progress. Report any persistent symptoms and continue therapy exactly as prescribed." ;
    :hasReference :R163 ;
    :interactsWith :S173 .

:ITN255 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN255" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Higher levels of Nitrofurantoin may build up in the blood, increasing the risk of side effects. At the same time, lower levels in the urine may reduce its ability to effectively kill bacteria in urinary tract infections." ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Probenecid reduces the kidney's ability to remove Nitrofurantoin from the body through urine. This causes the drug to stay longer in the bloodstream instead of being properly excreted into the urine where it is needed to treat infection." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Avoid using together unless prescribed by a doctor. The healthcare provider may monitor closely for side effects or adjust the treatment if necessary." ;
    :hasReference :R165 ;
    :interactsWith :S174 .

:ITN256 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN256" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Increased blood levels may raise the chance of side effects, while decreased urinary levels may reduce the drug's effectiveness in treating urinary infections." ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Sulfinpyrazone also decreases the excretion of Nitrofurantoin by the kidneys. This changes the normal balance of the drug in the body." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Use with caution and only under medical supervision. Report any unusual side effects or persistent infection symptoms." ;
    :hasReference :R165 ;
    :interactsWith :S175 .

:ITN257 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN257" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Lower absorption can reduce the amount of medicine reaching the urine. making treatment less effective. The infection may not fully clear." ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Magnesium Trisilicate reduces the absorption of Nitrofurantoin from the stomach and intestines. This means less of the antibiotic enters the bloodstream." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Avoid taking magnesium-containing antacids at the same time. If necessary, separate doses by several hours. Consult a healthcare provider before combining." ;
    :hasReference :R165 ;
    :interactsWith :S176 .

:ITN258 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN258" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "The combined use may decrease the overall antibacterial action, leading to reduced treatment effectiveness and possible treatment failure." ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Quinolone antibacterials may have antagonistic effects when used together with Nitrofurantoin. This means the medicines may reduce each other's effectiveness." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Avoid combining these antibiotics unless specifically directed by a physician. Follow medical advice carefully." ;
    :hasReference :R165 ;
    :interactsWith :S177 .

:ITN259 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN259" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Reduced antibacterial activity may occur, leading to incomplete treatment of urinary tract infections." ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Carbonic anhydrase inhibitors reduce the effectiveness of Nitrofurantoin by making the urine less acidic. Nitrofurantoin works better in acidic urine." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Use cautiously. The doctor may monitor treatment response and adjust therapy if needed." ;
    :hasReference :R165 ;
    :interactsWith :S178 .

:ITN260 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN260" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "The medicine may not work as effectively, and the infection may persist or return." ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "Urinary alkalinisers increase urine pH (make urine more alkaline), which can decrease the activity of Nitrofurantoin." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Avoid unnecessary use of urinary alkalinisers while taking Nitrofurantoin. Inform your doctor about all medications being used." ;
    :hasReference :R165 ;
    :interactsWith :S179 .

:ITN261 a :Interaction ;
    rdfs:label "ITN261" ;
    :hasClinicalEffects "Not Specified" ;
    :hasInteractionDescription "The action of sulfonamides may be antagonized by paminobenzoic acid and its derivatives, particularly potassium aminobenzoate and the procaine group of local anesthetics." ;
    :hasManagementAdvice "Not Specified" ;
    :hasReference :R166 ;
